      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### What You Would Need Instead\n\nFor stability constants at **200 °C / 50 bar** (hydrothermal conditions), you would need to consult:\n\n- **Hydrothermal geochemistry databases** (e.g., SUPCRT92, GEMS, or the LLNL thermodynamic database)\n- **Specific literature** on high-temperature aqueous speciation (e.g., work by Shock, Helgeson, or Sverjensky)\n- **Extrapolation models** such as the Helgeson–Kirkham–Flowers (HKF) equation of state, which can predict stability constants at elevated T and P from 25 °C reference values\n\n> **Note:** At 200 °C and 50 bar, water is still liquid (the saturation pressure of water at 200 °C is ~15.5 bar, so 50 bar keeps it liquid). This is a classic hydrothermal regime relevant to geothermal systems, nuclear reactor coolants, and ore deposit formation — but it is outside the scope of SRD-46.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 database (queried directly)*",
